---
/**
 * context-engineering 0006 · Figure 4 — "LLM-as-judge" scoring faithfulness &
 * relevance at scale, with its caveats.
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from the source lesson HTML (figure + svg + figcaption incl. the
 * footnote <sup>). Lives as an .astro component so the kebab-case SVG attributes
 * render byte-for-byte (see Fig1's header for the full rationale).
 *
 * The markers this figure references (arw) are inlined into its own <defs>, since
 * the MDX has no shared <body> <defs> block.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 600 168"
        role="img"
        aria-label="A judge model scores answer-context pairs for faithfulness and relevance, with caveats listed beside it."
    >
        <defs>
            <marker
                id="arw"
                viewBox="0 0 10 10"
                refX="8.5"
                refY="5"
                markerWidth="7"
                markerHeight="7"
                orient="auto-start-reverse"
                ><path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="#6b675f"></path></marker
            >
        </defs>
        <text x="300" y="18" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >LLM-AS-JUDGE &mdash; grade faithfulness &amp; relevance automatically</text
        >
        <rect x="30" y="38" width="150" height="74" rx="8" fill="#eef2f7" stroke="#1f3a5a"></rect>
        <text x="105" y="62" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >answer +</text
        >
        <text x="105" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >retrieved context</text
        >
        <text x="105" y="96" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >+ question / ground truth</text
        >
        <rect
            x="225"
            y="38"
            width="150"
            height="74"
            rx="8"
            fill="#f6eef7"
            stroke="#b5179e"
            stroke-width="2"></rect>
        <text x="300" y="68" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#b5179e"
            >Judge model</text
        >
        <text x="300" y="86" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >scores each metric 0&ndash;1</text
        >
        <rect x="420" y="38" width="150" height="74" rx="8" fill="#e9f3ec" stroke="#2f5d3a"></rect>
        <text x="495" y="62" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >scalar scores</text
        >
        <text x="495" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >faithfulness · relevance</text
        >
        <text x="495" y="96" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >per call, at scale</text
        >
        <line x1="180" y1="75" x2="223" y2="75" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line x1="375" y1="75" x2="418" y2="75" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <text x="300" y="138" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-style="italic" fill="#9a2417"
            >Caveats: judge bias (verbosity, position, self-preference) · needs calibration vs human
            labels · not free</text
        >
        <text x="300" y="156" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#6b675f"
            >Use it to scale grading you've spot-validated against humans — not as ground truth
            itself.</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        Human labels don't scale to every call; an <b>LLM-as-judge</b> approximates them cheaply for faithfulness
        and relevance. Treat its scores as a calibrated proxy — anchor a sample to human judgments and
        watch for known judge biases.<sup><a href="#s5" id="r5">5</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
